  "opinion": "As a self-taught electrician with a master's in engineering who grew up in a working-class neighborhood in Bologna, I've seen firsthand how stereotype threat can quietly undermine talent in STEM. When I first started working in electrical installations, I'd often hear colleagues say things like 'You're not cut out for this' or 'Girls don't do this kind of work' - even when they were clearly wrong. These comments aren't just hurtful; they create a psychological barrier that makes people doubt their abilities. From my experience, the best way to address this is through community-building. I've noticed that when people feel they belong in a group, they perform better. In my workshop, I've started organizing informal after-hours sessions where people from all backgrounds can share their skills without judgment. It's not about changing the system overnight, but about creating spaces where everyone feels safe to try. As someone who migrated to Italy and had to navigate language barriers, I know how important it is to build trust. The key is to focus on individual strengths rather than stereotypes. When we stop asking 'Can they do this?' and start asking 'What can they contribute?', we unlock potential that's been hidden for too long. This approach has helped me see more diverse talent in my work, and it's something I'd encourage anyone in STEM to try.",
